properties.Name: FinancialProduct
properties.Description: A financial product or service offered to customers.

Columns.Name: ProductId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Product.

Columns.Name: FinancialProductName
Columns.Description: The name of the Financial Product, which normally corresponds to the 'marketing name' of the Financial Product.

Columns.Name: FinancialProductDescription
Columns.Description: The description of the Financial Product.

Columns.Name: IssuerId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an Issuer.

Columns.Name: PurchaseRequirementsStatement
Columns.Description: A statement describing the requirements associated with purchasing the Financial Product.

Columns.Name: InvestmentObjectiveStatement
Columns.Description: A statement describing the investment objectives that the Financial Product addresses or intends to address.

Columns.Name: DeliveryInstructionsStatement
Columns.Description: The delivery instructions associated with the security.

Columns.Name: SalesPolicyStatement
Columns.Description:
The statement regarding the sales policy of the commercial paper.

Ex:

Sales Policies: Notes are offered directly to investors in discount or interest-bearing form.

Columns.Name: SettlementTermsStatement
Columns.Description: The terms of the physical delivery of the underlying financial product or cash.

Columns.Name: MinimumInvestmentAmount
Columns.Description: The minimum investment amount to purchase the financial product.

Columns.Name: MinimumInitialInvestmentAmount
Columns.Description: The minimum amount that may be initially invested in the Financial Product.

Columns.Name: MinimumAdditionalInvestmentAmount
Columns.Description: The minimum additional or subsequent investment amount to purchase the associated financial product.

Columns.Name: MaximumPurchaseAmount
Columns.Description:
The maximum purchase amount that may be purchased.

Ex:
The maximum T Bill investment allowed is $1 million dollars.

Columns.Name: NormalTradingUnit
Columns.Description:
The standard minimum size of trading a unit of the associated type of security.

Stocks have a normal trading unit normally of 100 shares.
Some inactive stocks may have a normal trading unit of as low as 10 shares.
Any security trading for less than a round lot is called an odd lot trade.

Columns.Name: IssuingDenomination
Columns.Description:
The face value or 'denominated amount' of the commercial paper offered.

Commercial paper is usually issued with denominations of $100,000 or more. Therefore, smaller investors can only invest in commercial paper indirectly through money market funds.

Columns.Name: TradingUnit
Columns.Description:
The trading unit associated with the Financial Product.

Ex:
- share
- bond
- dollar/currency
- oz/gold future contract

Columns.Name: ParValueAmount
Columns.Description: Equal to the Nominal or face value of a security.

Columns.Name: CusipNumber
Columns.Description: The CUSIP Number is issued by the Cusip Service Bureau. It is the number used by the brokerage industry to distinguish between the tens of thousands of public companies whose shares trade in the United States.

Columns.Name: IsoCurrencyCode
Columns.Description: The ISO 4217 currency code.

Columns.Name: FinancialProductTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Financial Product Type.

Columns.Name: RegisteredDate
Columns.Description: The date that the financial product was registered for sale.

Columns.Name: FirstPublicTradedDate
Columns.Description: The first date that the Financial Product is publicly traded.

Columns.Name: LastTradingDate
Columns.Description: The final day under an exchange's rules during which Trading may take Place in a particular futures or options contract.

Columns.Name: IssueMethodId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an Issue Method.

Columns.Name: DematerializedSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
A financial product that is represented only in electronic form.  

Purchases are only effected via book entry.

Columns.Name: RegisteredSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
A security in which the issuer or registrar acting on behalf of the issuer maintains a record of owners of the security.

This usually requires that the seller's name of the security is replaced by the buyers name on the register.

Columns.Name: BookEntrySecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
A security that is not represented by a certificate.

For example, some purchases and sales of municipal bonds are simply recorded to a customer account and no certificate changes hands.    It reduces paperwork.

Columns.Name: RematerializedSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates security holdings that were previously in electronic form but have been replaced by certificate form.

Columns.Name: ConvertibleFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description:
A corporate security, typically preferred shares or bonds, that can be exchanged for a set number of another form of financial product at a pre-defined price.

A convertible feature is an added incentive to enhance the marketability of the financial product.

For investors, convertibles normally combine higher income potential than from common stock plus greater appreciation than from bonds.

Columns.Name: ListedSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the stock or bond has been accepted for trading by one of the registered securities exchanges in the US.

The advantages of being listed are:

(1)  Orderly market

(2)  Liquidity

(3)  Fair price determinations

(4)  Accurate and continuous reporting on sales and quotations

(5)  Information on listed companies

(6)  Strict regulations

Columns.Name: UnlistedSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that is not listed on any exchange.

Columns.Name: BearerSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: A security in which the issuer has no ability to record the owner of the security and where proof of ownership is the physical possession of the security certificate.

Columns.Name: NotRatedFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that rating services and mercantile agencies have not rated the associated security, company or financial product.

The abbreviation NR is used for Not Rated Financial Products.

Columns.Name: MarginableSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates that the associated financial product is marginable.

Not all securities may be purchased on margin.

Columns.Name: DerivativeFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description: Financial instrument whose price is based on an underlying security--for example, an option's value can be derived either from its underlying stock, stock index, or future (dependent upon the type of option).

Columns.Name: ExemptSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: Securities that are not subject to the registration requirements of the Securities Act of 1933. Exempt securities also include securities that do not have to follow certain provisions of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 in terms of margin, registration of dealers who make a market in them, and certain reporting requirements. Examples of exempt securities are municipal bonds, governments and bank securities.

Columns.Name: InactiveFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description: Security that trades infrequently and has such a low volume that it makes the security illiquid.

Columns.Name: DualListedFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that is registered for trading on more than one exchange.

Columns.Name: WithWarrantsFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that trades with warrants as apart of the issue. The abbreviation "WW" is used in newspaper stock listings.

Columns.Name: IntraStateFinancialProductOfferingIndicator
Columns.Description: A new securities' issue that will only be sold to investors in one state and who are residents of that state. An intra-state offering is exempt from filing provisions of the Securities Exchange Act of 1933 under Rule 147.

Columns.Name: LetterSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
A security that is not registered with the SEC and thus, cannot be sold in the marketplace.

The issues are sold under an investment letter in which the purchaser states the purchase is for investment purposes and not for resale. The certificates have a restrictive legend that indicates they are not registered. Because the investment letter is essential to the security's issuance, this
 type of security is called either "letter security", "letter stock", or "letter bond".

Columns.Name: MarginableFinancialProductIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that may be bought or sold in a margin account. Regulation T of the Federal Reserve Board determines which securities are eligible.

Columns.Name: AgencySecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: A security, usually a bond, issued by a U.S. government agency. Agency securities are exempt from state and local taxes. also called U.S. Government Agency Security.

Columns.Name: ConvertibleSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that can be converted into common stock at the option of the security holder, including convertible bonds and convertible preferred stock.

Columns.Name: DualListingIndicator
Columns.Description: A security that is listed on more than one exchange--either the New York Stock Exchange and a regional exchange or the American Stock Exchange and a regional exchange. However, a security may not be listed on both the New York and American stock exchanges. Being dual listed increases the liquidity of a security.

Columns.Name: ExemptFromFederalTaxesIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates whether the financial product is exempt from federal taxes.

Note that tax-free investments result in earnings that are tax-free.   However, capital gains from buying and selling individual securities are not tax-free.  Additionally, capital gains earned and distributed by tax-free funds are subject to federal, state and local taxes.

The income from some municipal bonds are subject to the federal alternate minimum tax (AMT), which is a tax that applies to certain high-income individuals.

Columns.Name: ExemptFromStateTaxesIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the financial product is exempt from state taxes.

Columns.Name: ExemptFromLocalTaxesIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the financial product is exempt from local taxes.

Columns.Name: FinancialProductCategoryId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Financial Product Category.

Columns.Name: FungibleSecurityIndicator
Columns.Description:
Indicates whether ownership of securities that are interchangeable with each other and in which no specific certificates are assigned to any one of the owners ('co-mingled securities).   

The record of ownership is held electronically.

Columns.Name: IpoIndicator
Columns.Description:
A corporation's first offering of stock to the general public.

IPO's are the primary opportunity for existing investors and venture capitalists to make large profits.    Their shares will be given a market value reflecting the fair market value of the company, while they have shares obtained at much lower evaluations.

A company's first sale of stock to the public. Securities offered in an IPO are often, but not always, those of young, small companies seeking outside equity capital and a public market for their stock. Investors purchasing stock in IPOs generally must be prepared to accept very large risks for the possibility of large gains. IPO's by investment companies (closed end funds) usually contain underwriting fees which represent a load to buyers.

Columns.Name: NonFungibleCertificateIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates ownership that is assigned to specific owners rather than a pool of owners.

Columns.Name: OfferingDate
Columns.Description: The date on which the stock will first be available for sale to the public.

Columns.Name: PrimaryValueDate
Columns.Description:
The earliest date that settlement can occur on a new issue or securities.

This is also known as the 'Deferred Delivery Date'.

Columns.Name: SubjectToAmtIndicator
Columns.Description: The income from some municipal bonds are subject to the federal alternate minimum tax (AMT), which is a tax that applies to certain high-income individuals.
